did.abstract: The papers of William Hewlett document his professional and personal life, covering his many activities outside of Hewlett-Packard Company, how he invested his time and money, and his engagement with many organizations and individuals in business, politics, science, and academia.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: The collection is open for research, with the exception of a few boxes. Both Series 2: Financial and Series 4: Properties and Rentals each contain one box closed until the year 2050 because of sensitive material related to litigation. All items in Series 15: Audiovisual Materials were digitized and should be viewed or listened to through the reading room. The box containing the original audiovisual media is closed. Series 16: Original Correspondence is also closed to researchers, and only meant for use by staff, due to fragility; photocopies have been made available.
Note that material must be requested at least 36 hours in advance of intended use.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The William Hewlett Papers consists of correspondence, photographs, financial records, reports, minutes, calendars, notes, hardware, videotapes, compact discs, newspaper clippings, publications, and other materials. The collection documents some parts of Hewlett’s personal and professional life, as well as his finances, philanthropy, and engagement with scientific, cultural, international, business, and civic organizations. Some material in the collection was created and filed by staff and individuals representing the family after William Hewlett passed away in 2001.

bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: William Hewlett was the co-founder of Hewlett-Packard, one of the most successful technology start-up companies in the history of Silicon Valley. He and his business partner and longtime friend David Packard flipped a coin to determine the order of their names when starting their company. Following the tremendous success of Hewlett-Packard, he became well known for his philanthropy, donating millions of dollars from his fortune to support various causes. In 1966, he and his wife established the William and Flora Hewlett Foundation. Today the private foundation is among the largest in the United States.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The William Hewlett Papers is arranged into 16 series, Series 1: General Correspondence, Series 2: Financial, Series 3: Memberships/Boards, Series 4: Properties and Rentals, Series 5: Biographical and Family History, Series 6: Subject Files, Series 7: Calendars, Series 8: William and Flora Hewlett Foundation, Series 9: Los Trancos Baseball and San Francisco Giants, Series 10: International Travel and Foreign Aid Trips, Series 11: Honors, Certificates, and Gifts, Series 12: Medical Records, Series 13: Collected Resources and Publications, Series 14: Hardware and Programming, Series 15: Audiovisual Materials, Series 16: Original Correspondence, and Series 17: Addenda 2016-122.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: While Special Collections is the owner of the physical and digital items, permission to examine collection materials is not an authorization to publish. These materials are made available for use in research, teaching, and private study. Any transmission or reproduction beyond that allowed by fair use requires permission from the owners of rights, heir(s) or assigns.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Contains mostly letters, copies of outgoing correspondence, printed e-mails, and telegrams, interspersed with supplemental material, such as invitations, newsletters, newspaper clippings, photographs, notes, cards, and brochures.

The series documents Hewlett's correspondence with friends, family, colleagues, acquaintances, organizations, academic institutions, and strangers. The content of correspondence regards Hewlett-Packard, events, general discussions, in-person meetings, business, family, travel, his personal life, and other topics.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Series 1: General Correspondence is arranged into two subseries. Subseries A: Alphabetical and Subseries B: Chronological.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Through much of his life William Hewlett was active with prominent organizations, serving on their board or as a member. Although not are all represented in the collection, some groups Hewlett was involved with are:

American Academy of Arts and Sciences - Hewlett was elected Fellow in 1970 for Class I:5 (Engineering Sciences and Technologies) Walter Hewlett was also elected as a Fellow in 1999 for Class III:5 (Archaeology, Anthropology, Sociology, Geography, and Demography).
American Association for the Advancement of Science – Hewlett was elected Member in 1973.

American Institute of Electrical Engineers (in 1963 the American Institute of Electrical Engineers merged with the Institute of Radio Engineers to form the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers) – Hewlett was elected Fellow in 1959.
American Philosophical Society – Hewlett was elected Member At Large in 1981 for Class V (Administrator).
American University of Beirut International Advisory Board – Hewlett became a Member from 1991-2001.
Bohemian Club – Hewlett was a Member from 1948-2001. From 1949-2001 he was a Member of the Highlanders’ Camp at the Bohemian Grove.
California Academy of Sciences – Hewlett was a Trustee from 1963-1968. He served on the Building and Operations Committee. From 1968-2001 he was an Honorary Trustee.
California Manufacturers Association – Hewlett was a Director from 1959-1963.

Carnegie Institution of Washington – Hewlett served on the Board of Trustees from 1971-1990. He was the Chairman of the Board from 1980-1986. He was elected Chairman of the Nominating Committee from 1974-1976. He also served on the Astronomy Committee from 1974-1976 and the Executive and Finance Committee from 1980-1985.
Century Association – Hewlett was a Member from 1971-2001.
Chase Manhattan Bank (became JP Morgan Chase) – Hewlett served as Director from 1969-1980.

Chrysler Corporation – Hewlett was elected to the Board of Directors from 1966-1983. He served on the Executive Committee from 1976-1978, the Compensation and Benefits Committee 1967-1983 and the Nominating Committee from 1981-1983. He was the Chairman of the Compensation and Benefits Committee from 1973-1983.
Conservation International Science Advisory Committee – Hewlett served as a Member from 1993-2001.
Cypress Point Club – Hewlett was a Member from 1983-2001.
Drug Abuse Council in Washington, D.C. – Hewlett served as a Director from 1972-1974.
Eta Kappa Nu Association – Hewlett became an Eminent Member in 1999.
FMC Corporation – Hewlett was a Director from 1965-1974.
Foothills Tennis and Swimming Club – Hewlett was a Member from 1957-1975.
The Franklin Institute – Hewlett was elected as a Life Fellow Member in 1976.
Hexcel Products Incorporated – Hewlett was a Director from 1956-1965. He served on the Executive Committee during at least 1961.
Institute of Electrical and Electronic Engineers – Hewlett was elected a Life Fellow in 1948 (then the Institute of Radio Engineers).

Institute of Radio Engineers (in 1963 the American Institute of Electrical Engineers merged with the Institute of Radio Engineers to form the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers) – Hewlett served as a Director from 1949-1957. In 1954 he served as the President.
Instrument Society of America – Hewlett was elected as an Honorary Member from 1963-2001.
J.I. Case Company – Hewlett served as a Director from 1964-1968.
Kaiser Foundation Hospital and Health Plan – Hewlett was a Director from 1972-1978.
Kern County Land Company – Hewlett served as a Director from 1961-1969. He served on the Executive Committee from 1965-1969.
Menlo Country Club – Hewlett was a Member from at least 1968-2001.
Mills College – Hewlett served as a Trustee from 1958-1968.
Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute – Hewlett served as a Director from 1987-1998. He was a Director Emeritus from 1998-2001.
National Academies’ Corporation – Hewlett was a Director from 1986-1996. From 1997-2001 he served as an Honorary Member.
National Academy of Engineers – Hewlett was elected as a Member in 1965.
National Academy of Sciences – Hewlett was elected to the Academy as Member in 1977. From 1989-2001 he served on the Presidents’ Circle.
National Institute of Medicine – Hewlett was a Member from 1971-1972.
Overseas Development Council – Hewlett was a Director from 1969-1977.
Pacific National Bank – Hewlett served as a Director from 1959-1966.
Pacific-Union Club – Hewlett was a Member from 1962-2001.
Palo Alto Club – Hewlett was a Member from 1954-2001.
Palo Alto-Stanford Hospital (became Stanford Medical Center) – Hewlett was the President from 1956-1958 and served as a Director from 1958-1962.
President’s General Advisory Committee on Foreign Assistance Programs – Hewlett was a Member from 1965-1968.
President’s Science Advisory Committee – Hewlett served as a Member from 1966-1969.

Public Policy Institute of California – Hewlett was a co-founder of the Institute (along with Roger Heyns and Arjay Miller) and donated the initial $70 million endowment. Walter B. Hewlett served as a Director from 1999-2014 and as the Chairman from 2009-2010. In 2015 he became Director Emeritus.
Quadrato della Radio Association (Bologna) – Hewlett became a Member in 1978.
RAND Corporation – Hewlett was elected as a Trustee from 1962-1972.
San Francisco Bay Area Council – Hewlett was a Director from 1969-1981.
San Francisco Foundation – Hewlett served as a Trustee from 1962-1970. He became a Trustee Emeritus from 1993-2001.
San Francisco Fly Casting Club – Hewlett was a Member from at least 1978-2001.
San Francisco Regional Panel of the Commission on White House Fellows – Hewlett served as a Member from 1969-1970. He was the Chairman in 1970.
San Francisco Symphony – Hewlett served on the Board of Governors from at least 1985-1989. He was a Life Governor from 1990-2001.
Save-the-Redwoods League – Hewlett served as a Council Member from at least 1985-1989.
Sierra Club – Hewlett was a Member from at least 1953-1971.
Stanford Alumni – Hewlett was a Member from at least 1977-1998.
Stanford Associates – Hewlett was a Member from at least 1955-1998. He was on the Board of Governors from 1958-1960.

Stanford Center for Economic Policy Research (became the Stanford Institute for Economic Policy Research) – Hewlett served as a Director of the Advisory Board from 1982-1993. He was the Chairman from at least 1985-1986.
Stanford Faculty Club – Hewlett was elected as an Honorary Member from 1989-2001.
Stanford University – Hewlett served as a Trustee from 1963-1974. He was Vice-President from 1965-1974. His wife Flora Hewlett served as a Trustee from 1975-1977.
The Technology Center of Silicon Valley Advisory Council – Hewlett was a Member 1987-1988.
University Club of Palo Alto – Hewlett was a Member from 1965-1989.
University Corporation for Atmospheric Research Foundation – Hewlett served as a Director from 1986-1988.
Utah International – Hewlett was a Director from 1974-1985. He was on the Executive Committee from 1984-1985.
Ward Water Creek Company – Hewlett was a Member from 1961-1996. He resigned as a Director in 1996.
Watkins-Johnson Company – Hewlett was elected as a Director from 1958-1965.
Wells Fargo International Advisory Council – Hewlett served a Member from 1986-1992.

Western Electronic Manufacturers Association (became the American Electronics Association and later TechAmerica) – Hewlett-Packard Company and 25 of its suppliers formed the Association in 1943. Hewlett was Chairman of the San Francisco Section in 1948.
Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution – Hewlett was an Honorary Trustee from 1992-1993.
Wooley Camp Association – Hewlett was a Member from 1951-1995.
World Affairs Council of Northern California – Hewlett was a Member from at least 1978-2000.

custodhist.p: These papers appear to resemble organizational records of the Institue of Radio Engineers. Hewlett served as the Director, President, and on the Technical Papers Committee of the organization. It is possible he gained possesion of them when he assumed one of those roles. A letter in this folder from Noel Eldred to Leonard Black dated December 30, 1937 mentions how Black would receive all "papers, records, etc. of the IRE" from Carl Penther. So it is possible these papers changed hands multiple times as different people took over their responsibility.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: William Hewlett owned and rented a number of properties within his lifetime. Most of which were in California. Different family members at times rented and lived in homes owned by Hewlett. As a venture with his longtime friend and Business partner David Packard, he owned and operated several cattle ranches. San Felipe Ranches was the top organization of a 3 ranches that the Hewlett and Packard families owned: Merced Ranch (near Merced California), San Felipe Ranch (Santa Clara County, California) and Idaho Ranch (in Idaho and Montana). William Hewlett and David Packard started involving their children in leadership roles to prepare to pass it on to them. Ultimately the Merced and Idaho ranches were sold and the San Felipe Ranch had a conservation easement agreement with The Nature Conservancy that allowed for continuing cattle ranching and the families to build a limited number of personal residences as well as conserving the land for wildlife and from development in perpetuity.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The series consists of correspondence, bills, leases, contracts, maps, meetings minutes, building plans, tax records, newspaper clippings, and other material. Some of the records are from after William Hewlett passed away and document the Hewlett and Packard families' efforts to come to a consensus on what the future of the properties should be. Not all of the bills and invoices were kept in the collection. In some instances only a sample was retained. Some folders with them contain information on who was living at a certain property, as well as details about the property and household possessions.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: These were meetings of the Hewlett and Packard families. Originally shareholders were David Packard, William Hewlett, and Flora Hewlett. Gradually the children of both families also became Shareholders and took on more leadership roles. The meetings regarded the operation of the Ranches - operating budgets, Board By-Laws, future of the ranches, composition of the Board, rights of the shareholders, ways to avoid passing on financial burdens to future generations, as well what the purpose of the ranch should be: land and wildlife conservation, historic cattle ranch and personal residences.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Includes correspondence, media guides, newspaper clippings, reports, brochures, financial records, and meeting minutes. Topics include stadium construction, a players' strike, owner-players negotiations, finances, territorial rights, the Oakland Athletics, and attendance. The series documents Hewlett's ownership and relation to the San Francisco Giants Major League Baseball team. After William Hewlett passed away (in 2001) the Los Trancos Baseball Inc. ownership share of the Giants was transferred to the William and Flora Hewlett Foundation.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: In 1992 the owner of the San Francisco Giants, Bob Lurie, sold the team to a group that was going to move the Giants to St. Petersburg, Florida. A group of civic minded investors mostly from the San Francisco Bay Area and led by Peter Magowan made a counter-offer that kept the Giants in San Francisco. Although Hewlett was not personally a baseball fan he participated in this venture because he wanted to do something for San Francisco. There is hardly any evidence of personal involvement with the team after the purchase. Los Trancos Baseball LLC was the name of the company which was created to manage his stake in the ownership. Los Trancos Baseball was a Class B Limited Partner. This partnership class, as opposed to Class A and General, did not mandatorily have to meet cash calls.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Serial No. 08387. The HP-35 was HP's first pocket calculator. It was introduced at a time when most calculators (including expensive desktop models) had only the four basic functions. The HP-35 was the first pocket calculator with transcendental functions and the first with RPN (reverse polish notation).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Serial No. USA 2241A00407. Unit contained in mock leather case with black metal nameplate reading, "William R. Hewlett". The HP-75c was HP's first portable computer. It ran BASIC, and came with 16K of RAM with an expansion port for additional RAM and 48K of ROM with 3 ROM expansion ports. It had a keyboard that was large enough to touch type on (about 95% of full size), a very readable one line alpha display and an HP-IL port that allowed it to be attached to almost anything.
